name: Diesel consumption; Diesel fired equipment; Variable power rating
description:
This process is part of the NETL Unit Process Library.  To access the library and the original dataset:
1) Navigate to the NETL LCA home page (http://www.netl.doe.gov/lca)
2) Then navigate to the “Unit Process Library” 
3) From the library, the unit process of interest can be found either through the "Complete Listing of the Unit Process Library link" or through the link to the "Unit Process Database" spreadsheet
4) For each process, a Data Sheet (DS) and Data File (DF) are available

BRIEF DESCRIPTION					
This parameterized unit process models air emissions and heat produced by a generic piece of diesel powered machinery (at least 55.9 kW (75 HP)) used during construction of buildings, roadways, infrastructure, pipelines, etc. Emission factors are for non-road equipment.

GOAL AND SCOPE
The scope of this unit process includes diesel consumption and fuel emissions associated with the use of diesel fired construction equipment. The unit process models a generalized off-road diesel engine emissions profile, where the diesel engines in question can be modeled as either between 55.9 and 130.5 kW (75 and 175 horsepower (HP)), or greater than 130.5 kW (175 HP). The process is based on the reference flow of 1 megajoule (MJ) of thermal energy from diesel fuel, as described below and shown in the associated documentation (see Citation and Associated Documentation section below).

This unit process is considered to be applicable across the United States. However, the analyst should note that some states or regions, such as California, may require adherence to more stringent emissions criteria than those contained in this process. This is considered a data limitation, since emissions factors for most of the pollutants addressed in this unit process do not include air pollutant emissions control/mitigation measures that are common in some states or regions.

This unit process is used under Life Cycle (LC) Stage #1 or #3, and may be applied for a variety of purposes where operation of construction machinery is needed. These may include, but are not limited to, facility commissioning and facility decommissioning. This unit process is typically modeled in parallel to other operations unit processes, in order to assess diesel consumption rates and airborne emissions factors associated with construction. Outputs from this process are not tracked, as reflected in the associated documentation (referenced below)

BOUNDARY AND DESCRIPTION
The rate of diesel consumption included in this unit process is based on a default lower heating value (LHV) for diesel of 39.02 MJ/L. Thus, the production of 1 MJ of thermal energy from diesel (i.e., the reference flow for this unit process) requires 0.256 L of diesel. Diesel LHV is included as an adjustable parameter, and can be modified as warranted, within the typical range for diesel LHV. 

Air emissions are calculated on a per MJ basis, based on data available from the US Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), the US Department of Energy (DOE), and other sources. Emissions of carbon dioxide, particulate matter, nitrogen oxides, and non-methane volatile organic carbons are estimated based on US EPA and DOE emissions factors (DOE 2007; Federal Register 2004). Emissions of sulfur dioxide were calculated stoichiometrically, based on the presumed use of 15 parts per million, ultra low sulfur diesel (ULSD) (DieselNet 2009a). Carbon monoxide is the only air emission factor that is modeled as dependent on engine horsepower: 0.0148 kg CO/L diesel for 55.9 through 130.5 kW (75 and 175 horsepower (HP)) engines, and 0.0104 kg CO/L for engines larger than 130.5 kW (175 HP)  (DieselNet 2009b). Engine size is included as an adjustable parameter, and can toggled via a binary switch between the two different power options. Finally, nitrous oxide, methane, and ammonia emissions were modeled based on data available from the DOE (2006).

An overview of the boundary of this unit process can be found in the associated documentation (see Citation and Associated Documentation section below). Emissions associated with the production and transport of diesel fuel are considered outside the boundary of this unit process. Within the boundary of the unit process, energy use and air emissions are quantified, as discussed previously. Unlike most unit processes, this process does not include any tracked output flows. Therefore, the process does not directly feed into another portion of the model, although energy use and air emissions are of course incorporated into model results.

The associated documentation (referenced below) contains: summaries of the relevant properties and assumptions used to calculate diesel use and air emissions; modeled input and output flows; and additional detail regarding input and output flows, including calculation methods.

CITATION AND ASSOCIATED DOCUMENTATION
This document should be cited as: 
National Energy Technology Laboratory (NETL). 2015. NETL Life Cycle Inventory Data – Unit Process: Diesel consumption; Diesel fired construction equipment; Variable power rating. U.S. Department of Energy, National Energy Technology Laboratory. Last Updated: September 2015 (version 01). Retrieved on [DATE] from [URL for this dataset].

This dataset is part of the NETL Unit Process Library.  The Library offers additional information concerning this dataset in the form of a Detailed Spreadsheet  Documentation (DS) file and a Process Documentation File (DF).  The DS file  is an Excel file that contains all of the parameters, inputs, and outputs for a given system as well as background data, calculations and quality scores.  The DF file is a PDF document that contains major assumptions and data sources that are the basis for each unit process.  The NETL Unit Process Library is located on the NETL website (netl.doe.gov) under Research / Energy Analysis / Energy Trends and Issues / Life Cycle Analysis / Unit Process Library.

Full citations for the DS and DF are given below:

DS File
National Energy Technology Laboratory (NETL). 2010. NETL Life Cycle Inventory Data – Unit Process: Combustion of Diesel. U.S. Department of Energy, National Energy Technology Laboratory. Last Updated: January 2015 (version 02). Retrieved on 09/30/2015 from:http://www.netl.doe.gov/File%20Library/Research/Energy%20Analysis/Life%20Cycle%20Analysis/UP_Library/DS_Stage5_O_Combustion_Of_Diesel_2015-02.xlsx.

DF File

processDocumentation.timeDescription: This data set is representative of best available public data from 01/01/2010 to 12/31/2010 and is not subject to limited usability within sub-time spans (e.g. summer, winter).
processDocumentation.technologyDescription: The unit process models a generalized off-road diesel engine emissions profile, where the diesel engines in question can be modeled as either between 55.9 and 130.5 kW (75 and 175 horsepower (HP)), or greater than 130.5 kW (175 HP). This unit process is considered to be applicable across the United States. However, the analyst should note that some states or regions, such as California, may require adherence to more stringent emissions criteria than those contained in this process. This is considered a data limitation, since emissions factors for most of the pollutants addressed in this unit process do not include air pollutant emissions control/mitigation measures that are common in some states or regions.
processDocumentation.modelingConstantsDescription: All elementary and technosphere flows are calculated on a functional unit basis. Calculations involving combustion primarily to generate useful work are done using lower heating values (LHV) and calculations involving combustion primarily to generate useful heat are done using higher heating values (HHV). Unless explicitly stated in the associated reference documents applicable calculations assumed standard atmospheric temperature and pressure (SATP).
